1 Learning Outcomes

  • Use R and R Studio tools to build packages for personal or distributed use
  • Document functions using Roxygen2 tags.

1.1 References

  • R Packages Wickham and Bryan (n.d.)
  • Package Workflow Blog Post (“Usethis Workflow for Package Development” n.d.) -Writing R Extensions (“Writing R Extensions” n.d.)

1.2 Introduction

  • In R, a package is the fundamental unit of shareable code.
  • A package bundles together code, data, documentation, and tests, and is easy to share with others.
  • As of 2/10/20, there were over 18,000 packages in public R repositories.
  • This huge variety of packages is one of the reasons that R is so successful: the chances are that someone has already solved a problem that you’re working on, and you can benefit from their work by downloading their package.

  • Popular packages cover the Data Science life cycle.

  • You already know how to use packages:
    • Install them from CRAN with install.packages("x").
    • Load them in R with library("x").
    • Get help on them with package?x and help(package = "x").
  • You can write your own, not just use other people’s.
    • Save your time by enabling reuse across multiple projects
    • Share with others by bundling your code into a package so any R user can use it.
    • Some people use the package as the fundamental unit of their analysis projects, not just for code management See Robert Flight’s 2014 blog (“Analyses as Packages” n.d.)

1.3 Getting Ready

  • Use the console to install several packages to help you create your own packages
#install.packages(c("devtools", "roxygen2", "testthat", "knitr", "usethis"))
  • R Studio has tools to help you use these packages as you go through the package development workflow
    • Check you have installed the R Studio API package and have the latest version

#devtools::install_github("r-lib/devtools")
  • You’ll also need a C compiler and a few other command line tools. If you don’t already have them, R Studio will install them for you. Otherwise:
    • On Windows, download and install Rtools. NB: this is not an R package!
    • On Mac, make sure you have either XCode (available for free in the App Store) or the “Command Line Tools for Xcode”. You’ll need to have a (free) Apple ID.

2 Creating Your Package

2.1 Packages have a Standard File Structure

  • The structure is designed to enforce rules for working well with Base R and other compliant packages
  • Repositories often require specific implementations of the files to allow posting

-The smallest usable package has three components: + An R/ directory, with R code + A basic DESCRIPTION file, with package metadata + A basic NAMESPACE file

2.2 The First Step: Picking a Name for your Package

  • Before you can create your first package, you need to come up with a name for it.
  • There are three formal requirements:
    • The name can only consist of letters, numbers and periods,
    • It must start with a letter, and
    • It cannot end with a period.
    • Note: you cannot use either hyphens or underscores and you should not use periods to avoid confusion with some other structures
  • Best Practices
    • Avoid using both upper and lower case letters.
    • Pick a unique name you can easily Google.
      • Check if a name exists on CRAN by loading http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/[PACKAGE_NAME].
      • Replace [PACKAGE NAME] with your potential name, e.g., http://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/dplyr
      • If you get a package page, pick a new name!
      • You can also use the available package to check if your name is used elsewhere or has another meaning:
#install.packages("available")
library(available)
#available("ggplot2")
#available("rttest")
  • Find a word that evokes the problem and modify it so it’s unique:
    • plyr is generalization of the apply family, and evokes pliers.
    • lubridate makes dates and times easier.
  • Use abbreviations:
    • Rcpp = R + C++ (plus plus)
    • lvplot = letter value plots.
  • Add an extra R:
    • stringr provides string tools.
    • tourr implements grand tours (a visualization method).
  • If you’re creating a package that talks to a commercial service, check the branding guidelines. For example, rDrop is not called rDropbox because Dropbox prohibits any applications from using the full trademarked name.

2.3 Creating a Package with R Studio

  • Pick a location (path) for your new package that is NOT in an existing R Studio Project or Git Repository
  • You can create packages using the console.
  • The usethis package has functions designed to ease the process
    • create_package(path) creates an R package and invokes a new R Studio Session
#create_package("../../../../R_packages/testpackage")

create_package() Rresults

2.3.1 Files

  • .gitignore anticipates Git usage and ignores some standard, behind-the-scenes files created by R and R Studio.
  • .Rbuildignore lists files that we need to have around but that should not be included when building the R package from source. More in 4.3.1.
  • DESCRIPTION provides metadata about your package. We edit this shortly.
  • NAMESPACE declares the functions your package exports for external use and the external functions your package imports from other packages. At the moment, it holds temporary-yet-functional placeholder content.
  • The R/ directory is the “business end” of your package. It will soon contain .R files with function definitions.
  • packagename.Rproj is the file that makes this directory an R Studio Project.
  • .Rproj.user, if you have it, is a directory used internally by R Studio.

2.4 Testing initial creation

  • Notice there is a new Build tab in the same pane as Environment and History.
  • Your package is empty of code but you can test if it works from a package perspective
  • In the new R Studio session go to Build Tab (or the “Build menu”) and select “Install and Restart”

Build, Install and Restart

2.5 Establish Git capabilities in the new session console

  • Load the usethis package for multiple steps that follow.

  • The package directory is an R source package and an R Studio Project.

  • Now make it also a Git repository, with use_git().

#library(usethis)
#usethis::use_git()
  • You will get asked to commit some files so do so. This will help establish the Head pointer for the project/package/repo
  • You will also get asked to restart so it can set up the Git Pane in R Studio.
  • If you go into your computer file manager and look for hidden files you should see a .git folder now in your package directory (you cannot see these in the R Studio Files Tab)

3 One Time Actions

3.1 Update the DESCRIPTION file.

  • Make sure the Authors@R is populated correctly and modify the Title and Description fields.
    • aut - Author
    • cre - Creator
      ## Choose a License for the package
  • Use one of the following functions
#use_mit_license("copywrite holder name")
#use_gpl3_license()
#use_apl2_license()
#use_cc0_license()
  • See Choose a License for more info

3.2 Add a readme file for Git Hub for new users

  • Use use_readme_rmd() and you can edit it later.
  • Knit the README.Rmd file and then add and commit the files so everything is up to date.
  • The goal of the README.md is to answer the following questions for new users about your package:
    • Why should I use it?
    • How do I use it?
    • How do I get it?

  • On GitHub, the README.md will be rendered as HTML and displayed on the repository home page.

  • Hadley recommends structuring a README as follows:
    • A paragraph describing the high-level purpose of the package.
    • An example that shows how to use the package to solve a simple problem.
    • Installation instructions, giving code that can be copied and pasted into R.
    • An overview of the main components of the package. For more complex packages, point to vignettes.

3.3 Add a News File for updating current users on changes

  • A NEWS file helps people keep track of what is happening with the package
  • Use use_news_md() to create an markdown file NEWS.md you can edit
  • Recommended Structure
    • Show the current version number as a major heading
    • List the user-visible changes worth mentioning.
  • Workflow
    • As you are developing your code for each new release, add a new header with the version number to the front of the file and then list the changes in a bullet list
    • Don’t discard old items; leave them in the file after the newer items. This way, a user upgrading from any previous version can see what is new.
    • If the NEWS file gets very long, move some of the older items into a file named ONEWS and put a note at the end referring the user to that file.
    • There is a newsmd package that may be of interest for long-term package development

4 Typical Workflow for Package Development

  • A typical workflow will be repeating the following steps i

    • Write some code
    • Restart R Session Cmd+Shift+F10 (Ctrl+Shift+F10 for Windows)
    • Build and Reload Cmd+Shift+B (Ctrl+Shift+B for Windows)
    • Test Package Cmd+Shift+T (Ctrl+Shift+T for Windows)
    • Check Package Cmd+Shift+E (Ctrl+Shift+E for Windows)
    • Document Package Cmd+Shift+D (Ctrl+Shift+D for Windows)
  • Writing code most likely includes writing functions.

  • This is helped by the use_r() function by adding and opening a .R file for you to write your function in. use_r("function_name")

The use_r() function is very important and you will using it a lot, + It creates the files in which you save your functions + It will also open the files if they are already created, - This makes navigating your R files much easier.

  • Once you have created your function it is time to add some tests!

  • This is done using the use_test() function, and it works much the same way as the use_r().

  • You often need to depend on another package in executing your code. To add a function to the imports field in the DESCRIPTION file use the use_package() function, e.g. use_package("dplyr")' + Special cases functions includeuse_rcpp(),use_pipe()anduse_tibble()`.

  • You may want to create an vignette as a nice piece of documentation of how you expect people to use the functions after you have added a bunch of capabilities to your package. An example would be use_vignette("How to do this cool analysis")

4.1 Writing Code

  • Suppose you wanted to create a function to concatenate the levels of two factors
#fbind <- function(a, b) {
#  factor(c(as.character(a), as.character(b)))
#}
#fbind(as.factor(c("dog","cat")),as.factor(c("gerbil","parakeet")))
  • All Code goes into the R/ directory
  • If you have already written your functions elsewhere, you can copy and paste into the R directory.

4.1.1 use_r("new_function_name") to open an or existing .R file

  • Create a new .R file for each function or closely related functions.
#use_r("fbind")
  • This opens up a tab in the Source pane with the new file name so you can enter your code
  • Put the definition of fbind() and only the definition of fbind() in R/fbind.R and save it.
    • Save documentation for later. Do not include any calls to libraries (yet)
    • Packages and scripts use different mechanisms to declare their dependency on other packages.

4.1.2 load_all()

  • Instead of using source(), we use a devtools function to access the function
  • load the devtools package with library using the console
  • Call load_all() to make fbind() available.

  • Test it in the console fbind(as.factor(c("dog","cat")),as.factor(c("gerbil","parakeet")))

  • Note: load all() only simulates the process of building, installing, and attaching the new package.
    • As packages grow, load_all() gives you a more accurate sense of how the package is developing than test driving functions defined in the global workspace.
    • It’s also faster than actually building, installing, and attaching the package.

  • You can commit the new file now

4.1.3 check() your package still works after your latest changes

  • The function worked on the command line. As we add more functions we want to see if all the moving parts of the package still work?
  • check() is a convenient way to run the shell command R CMD check for checking if an R package is in full working order, without leaving your R session.

4.1.4 Identify other packages needed in by your code with use_package()

  • You will probably need to include functions from other packages in your own package, e.g. %>%.
  • You can import functions from the “namespace” of other packages.
    • If you plan to submit a package to CRAN, this even applies to functions in packages that you think of as “always available”, such as stats::median() or utils::head().
  • Use use_package(), e.g., use_package("forcats") to declare your general intent to use some functions from the another package’s namespace
    • This adds the package to the “Imports” section of the DESCRIPTION file
  • Packages listed under Imports must be present for your package to work.
    • If your package is installed, those packages, if not already present, will be installed on your computer (devtools::load_all() also checks the packages are installed).
  • Adding a package dependency ensures that it’ll be installed. However, it does not mean that it will be attached along with your package (i.e., library(x)).
  • A best practice is to explicitly refer to external functions using the syntax package::function(). This makes it very easy to identify which functions live outside of your package. This is especially useful when you read your code in the future.
    • *Example: use forcats:fcount()** inside your function. This way you do not have to worry if the package is attached.
  • To import functions from a package, run use_package("packagename") and then use the roxygen2 tag @importFrom package func in your R file documentation e.g.,
    • @importFrom ggplot2 ggplot aes geom_bar coord_flip
  • To use the %>% operator run the function use_pipe(). This will add another file to the R directory and update NAMESPACE file to allow both import and export of %>%

4.2 Document each function to be exported with roxygen2

  • You saw the warning in check() about an undocumented function.
  • We must create a way to get help on ‘fbind()’
  • Every package should have a special R documentation file, man/fbind.Rd, written in an R-specific markup language that is sort of like LaTeX.
  • Luckily, we don’t necessarily have to author that directly.

4.2.1 roxygen2

  • We can write specially formatted comments right above fbind(), in its source file, and then let a package called roxygen2 handle the creation of man/fbind.Rd.
  • In R Studio, open R/fbind.R in the source editor and put the cursor somewhere in the fbind() function definition.
    • Do “Code > Insert roxygen skeleton”.
    • A set of special comments should appear above your function, in which each line begins with #'.
    • R Studio only inserts a bare bones template, so you will need to edit it to be useful.

4.2.2 roxygen parameters for functions

  • The first sentence is the title: that’s what you see when you look at help(package = mypackage) and is shown at the top of each help file. It should generally fit on one line, be written in sentence case, and not end in a full stop.

  • The second paragraph is the description: this comes first in the documentation and should briefly describe what the function does. The description should start with a capital letter and end with a full stop. It can span multiple lines (or even paragraphs) if necessary.

  • The skeleton should next list all the arguments of the function using the tag @param name
    • Document all arguments by describing the the argument type (e.g., string, numeric vector) and then, starting with a capital letter, a short description of the purpose of the parameter
    • You can document multiple arguments in one place by separating the names with commas (no spaces). For example, to document both x and y, you can write @param x,y Numeric vectors..

-The Details paragraphs come after the arguments and are optional. This could be several paragraphs to provide any other important details of how the function operates.

  • @return describes the output from the function. This is not always necessary, but is a good idea.

-@export1 identifies the functions you want others to have direct access to from your package. You may have written multiple “helper” functions for your package your users don’t need. Delete any @export tags for these helper functions to avoid adding extraneous name into your users namespace.

  • @examples provides executable R code showing how to use the function in practice. This is a very important part of the documentation because many people look at the examples first. Example code must work without errors as it is run automatically as part of R CMD check.
    • For the purpose of illustration, it’s often useful to include code that causes an error. \dontrun{} allows you to include code in the example that is not run.
    • Instead of including examples directly in the documentation, you can put them in separate files and use @example path/relative/to/package/root to insert them into the documentation. (Note that the @example tag here has no ‘s’.)

4.3 Use document() to create the Man(ual) Help files

  • Use document() to convert the new roxygen comments into man/fbind.Rd
  • You should see something like:
  • You should now be able to preview your help file for each function using ?fbind

  • Open NAMESPACE for inspection.

5 Other Actions: Testing and Writing Vignettes

5.1 Testing with use_testthat(), use_test() and test()

  • You tested fbind() informally, in a single example on the console. This is not repeatable and scalable.

  • Formalizing unit tests requires expressing a few concrete expectations about the correct fbind() result for various inputs.

  • First,declare our intent to write unit tests and to use the testthat package via use_testthat()
    • This initializes the unit testing machinery for your package. It adds
      • Suggests: testthat to DESCRIPTION,
      • creates the directory tests/testthat/, and
      • adds the script test/testthat.R.
  • However, it’s still up to YOU to write the actual tests!
    • Call use_test() to initialize a basic test file and open it for editing.
    • The helper use_test("function_name") opens and/or creates a test file stored under the tests/testthat folder.
    • add the example code into the test-fbind.r to create two tests.
    • look at the help for expect_identical()
test_that("fbind() binds factor (or character)", {
  x <- c("a", "b")
  x_fact <- factor(x)
  y <- c("c", "d")
  z <- factor(c("a", "b", "c", "d"))

  expect_identical(fbind(x, y), z)
  expect_identical(fbind(x_fact, y), z)
})

  • This tests if fbind() gives an expected result when combining two factors and a character vector and a factor.

  • attach the testthat package via library(testthat)
  • Run load_all()
  • Run this test interactively with test()
  • You can add more tests to your test-function_name file

  • You can then run multiple tests at once! via test():

5.2 Writing Vignettes

  • A vignette is a long-form guide to your package if you want to explain the details of your package.
    • A vignette can describe the problem your package is designed to solve and then show the reader how to solve it. - Examples: Use the R Studio Console to look up help for ggplot or rmarkdown
    • A vignette should divide functions into useful categories, and demonstrate how to coordinate multiple functions to solve problems.
  • Each vignette provides three things:
    • the original source file,
    • a readable HTML page or PDF, and
    • a file of R code
  • we’re going to use the R Markdown vignette engine provided by knitr

5.2.1 Create your first vignette, with:usethis::use_vignette("my-vignette")

  • Running usethis::use_vignette("my-vignette") will:
    • Create a vignettes/ directory.
    • Add the necessary dependencies to DESCRIPTION (i.e. it adds knitr to the Suggests and VignetteBuilder fields).
    • Create a draft vignette, vignettes/my-vignette.Rmd.
  • You can now edit and knit the vignettes R Markdown file as usual.

5.2.2 The vignette has special fields in the YAML Header

  • You can also add other YAML fields like author or date if desired,
  • The output type “rmarkdown::html_vignette” has been specifically designed to work well inside packages
  • Vignette: this contains a special block of metadata needed by R.
    • Modify the \VignetteIndexEntry to provide the title of your vignette as you’d like it to appear in the vignette index.
    • Leave the other two lines as is. They tell R to use knitr to process the file, and that the file is encoded in UTF-8 (the only encoding you should ever use to write vignettes).

5.2.3 Common problems:

  • The vignette builds interactively, but when checking, it fails with an error about a missing package you know is installed.
    • This means you’ve forgotten to declare that dependency in the DESCRIPTION (usually it should go in Suggests).
  • Everything works interactively, but the vignette doesn’t show up after you’ve installed the package.
    • Because R Studio’s “build and reload” doesn’t build vignettes, you may need to run devtools::install() instead.

6 Exercise Adding a Second Function

  • Let’s add a second function to the package: imagine we want a frequency table for a factor, as a regular data frame with nice variable names where the rows are sorted so that the most prevalent level is at the top.
  • Use use_r("fcount") to open a new file
  • Enter the following code in the file
#' Make a sorted frequency table for a factor
#'
#' @param x factor
#'
#' @return A tibble
#' @export
#' @examples
#' fcount(iris$Species)
fcount <- function(x) {
  forcats::fct_count(x, sort = TRUE)
}
  • Use load_all() to simulate the instantiation of the package
  • Manually Test on the command line with fcount(iris$Species)
  • Generate the associated help file via document().
  • Install using `install()
  • Use library to load into another workspace and test it
library(testpackage)
fcount(iris$Species)

6.1 use_github()

  • You can sync your local rep with Git Hub - AFTER you have created the Git Hub repo
  • Use the normal commands in the terminal
  • You can also set up an authorization token to enable you to use use_github() which can automate the process.

6.2 Coding Style with the styler package and `use_tidy_style()’

  • Package users like packages to be coded in accordance with the standards in the Tidyverse Style Guide
  • The styler package can assist with checking and updating code in a .R file to correspond to the style guide.
#install.packages("styler")
library(styler)
  • see help for styler
  • styler vignette(“An Introduction to Styler” n.d.)
  • Warning: This function will overwrite files! It is strongly suggested to only style files that are under version control or to first create a backup copy.
  • There are several helper functions in the usethis package as well
    • look for help on use_tidy or got to usethis Helper functions(“Helpers for Tidyverse Development — Tidyverse” n.d.)
